This works — it sums the array — but a few small improvements and edge-case checks will make it clearer, safer and (optionally) faster.

Quick tweaks
- Use the += operator: total += arr[i]; is shorter and idiomatic.
- Make sure total is declared and initialised before the loop (let total = 0;).
- If arr might be null/undefined, check it first (or default to []).

Readability alternatives
- for...of (clearer intent):
  let total = 0;
  for (const value of arr) total += value;

- reduce (declarative, returns a value):
  const total = arr.reduce((sum, value) => sum + value, 0);

Performance/edge cases
- If arr may change length during iteration, cache length: for (let i = 0, len = arr.length; i < len; i++) { ... }
- If arr may contain non-numbers or strings, coerce/validate elements to avoid concatenation or NaN:
  const total = arr.reduce((sum, v) => {
    const n = Number(v);
    return sum + (Number.isFinite(n) ? n : 0);
  }, 0);

When to keep the original
- The indexed for-loop is fine for performance-critical code and is perfectly acceptable if you prefer it. Just prefer += and ensure total is properly declared and initialised.

